Our instances shall be taken from the Seventh Satire: on v. 2 we have the note Camenas. lucentibus poetis—where the lecturer must have meant to explain tristes, while the scholar took down the least important part of the heading. In the same way in v. 7, Clio heads the following note-id est osti- arius uel eustos atrienses. Here the explanation is so curtailed as to be grammatically incomplete ; but this might be due to a wish for brevity. When, however, we see that the pupil has only taken down the last word of the clause (migraret in utria Clio), which the lecturer recalled for comment, we are inclined to set down the mutilated form of the note to the hurry of dictation.
